Why Is James Hardie Industries plc (ASX:JHX) Trading Below The Industry Average?



Andrew Edmonds 


            				July 8, 2017			        


 James Hardie Industries plc’s (ASX:JHX) current PE ratio of 23.8, compared to its industry’s 28.5, appears unjustified when we look at the company’s track record and projected earnings growth. See our latest analysis for JHX 
Is James Hardie Industries avaliable for a good price?
 One of the easiest ways to compare a company’s valuation relative to its industry is the PE ratio. While there is no set definition of what an acceptable PE should be, popular opinion is that a value of over 30 may get you in trouble. But there are always exceptions, such as high growth potential companies, primarily in the technology sector. Investors pay well beyond the 30-mark based on their steep growth projections.
 The price-to-earnings ratio of James Hardie Industries stands at 23.8, compared to the industry average of 28.5. On the surface, it appears relatively undervalued.We must assess the company’s earnings performance to judge whether it’s lower valuation against the industry is justified or the market is mispricing the company.
What does the track record say?
 While a clear indication of company’s track record is its top-line growth, the bottom-line growth becomes more important when the company has passed the initial growth phase as other priorities such operational efficiency kick-in.JHX delivered an impressive annual average earnings growth rate of 33.9% over the past five years. Its past growth rate would easily lie in the upper-end of the most mature and late-stage-growth industries.
 

 James Hardie Industries (ASX:JHX) Income Statement Jul 8th 17
 
 In addition to a strong performance over an extended period, James Hardie Industries’s last year’s growth in earnings of 13.8% stood above the industry’s 13.4%.When mature companies are growing faster than the overall industry, they generally do it by stealing the market share from competitors. However, if the entire industry is growing at a fast clip, the higher growth generally comes from capturing a larger chunk of that increasing pie, indicating a competitive advantage for the company.
What can we expect in the future?
 A multitude of factors can affect a company’s performance in the near future. These are broadly divided into two categories: external and internal. External factors such as regulatory environment and effective tax rate; and internal factors such as management.No matter how sophisticated an investor becomes, keeping a close eye on all these factors affecting a company and adjusting projections accordingly is a not an easy task. Thus, it seems reasonable to take analysts’ estimates at face value. And if not, we can agree that the mean of their estimates represents a decent gauge.
 JHX is covered by 7 analysts who by consensus are expecting a 28.6% increase in earnings over the next 3 years. That means that we can be expecting the EPS to grow to $0.86 levels.


 James Hardie Industries (ASX:JHX) Past Future Earnings Jul 8th 17
 
Final word
 Considering James Hardie Industries’s track record, expected earnings growth, and the price-to-earnings ratio, it appears to be trading at a reasonable valuation. There are other fundamental considerations related to its balance sheet and dividend history, which may change an investor’s perspective – See our latest analysis to find out!
Daniel Loeb has achieved 16.2% annualized returns over the last 20 years. What is he holding today?
Founder of the event-driven, value-oriented hedge fund Third Point, Daniel Loeb is one of the most successful activist investors on the market today. Explore his portfolio’s top holdings, see how he diversifies his investments, past performance and growth estimates. Click here to view a FREE detailed infographic analysis of Daniel Loeb’s investment portfolio. 




